    subgraph U1["Unit 1: Thinking Geographically"]
        U1S1["Can define geography as the study of spatial patterns and relationships on Earths surface"]
        U1S2["Can distinguish between physical geography and human geography"]
        U1S3["Can identify reference maps as showing natural and human-made features like boundaries and roads"]
        U1S4["Can identify thematic maps as showing specific spatial patterns of data"]
        U1S5["Can identify choropleth maps as using shading to show data by area"]
        U1S6["Can identify dot distribution maps as using dots to show density or occurrence"]
        U1S7["Can identify graduated symbol maps as using symbols of varying size to show quantities"]
        U1S8["Can identify isoline maps as using lines connecting points of equal value"]
        U1S9["Can identify cartograms as distorting area to represent data values"]
        U1S10["Can define absolute location using latitude and longitude coordinates"]
        U1S11["Can define relative location as the position of a place in relation to other places"]
        U1S12["Can distinguish between absolute distance measured in units and relative distance based on perception"]
        U1S13["Can distinguish between absolute direction using cardinal directions and relative direction"]
        U1S14["Can identify clustered spatial patterns on maps"]
        U1S15["Can identify dispersed spatial patterns on maps"]
        U1S16["Can identify linear spatial patterns on maps"]
        U1S17["Can define map scale as the ratio of distance on a map to actual distance on Earths surface"]
        U1S18["Can distinguish between large-scale maps showing small areas in detail and small-scale maps showing large areas"]
        U1S19["Can explain how map projections inevitably distort one or more of shape, area, distance, and direction"]
        U1S20["Can identify the Mercator projection as preserving shape but distorting area near the poles"]
        U1S21["Can identify equal-area projections as preserving area but distorting shape"]
        U1S22["Can define GIS as a computer system for capturing, storing, analyzing, and displaying spatial data"]
        U1S23["Can define GPS as a satellite-based system for determining precise absolute location"]
        U1S24["Can define remote sensing as collecting data about Earths surface from satellites or aircraft"]
        U1S25["Can distinguish between quantitative geographic data using numbers and qualitative geographic data using descriptions"]
        U1S26["Can identify fieldwork methods including interviews, surveys, travel logs, and field sketches"]
        U1S27["Can explain how geospatial data is used to influence government policy and create regulations"]
        U1S28["Can explain how geospatial data is used by businesses for site selection and marketing"]
        U1S29["Can define space as the physical area between two points on Earths surface"]
        U1S30["Can define place as a specific location with distinctive physical and human characteristics"]
        U1S31["Can define site as the internal physical and cultural characteristics of a place"]
        U1S32["Can define situation as the external location of a place relative to other places"]
        U1S33["Can define distance decay as the decreasing interaction between places as distance increases"]
        U1S34["Can define time-space compression as the reduction of travel and communication time between places"]
        U1S35["Can define spatial interaction as the flow of people, goods, and ideas between places"]
        U1S36["Can define pattern as the arrangement of features in a geographic space"]
        U1S37["Can define sustainability as using resources to meet present needs without compromising future generations"]
        U1S38["Can explain human-environment interaction as how humans modify and adapt to their natural surroundings"]
        U1S39["Can define natural resources as materials in the environment that humans value and use"]
        U1S40["Can distinguish between renewable and nonrenewable natural resources"]
        U1S41["Can explain environmental determinism as the idea that the physical environment controls human actions"]
        U1S42["Can explain possibilism as the idea that humans can adapt to and modify their environment"]
        U1S43["Can distinguish among local, national, regional, and global scales of analysis"]
        U1S44["Can explain how the same phenomenon may show different patterns at different scales of analysis"]
        U1S45["Can define formal regions as areas with uniform measurable characteristics"]
        U1S46["Can define functional regions as areas organized around a central node or focal point"]
        U1S47["Can define perceptual or vernacular regions as areas based on peoples informal sense of place"]
        U1S48["Can explain how regions are constructed by geographers as tools for spatial analysis"]
        U1S49["Can explain how regional boundaries can overlap and change over time"]
