    subgraph U2["Unit 2: Population and Migration Patterns and Processes"]
        U2S1["Can explain that population is unevenly distributed across Earths surface"]
        U2S2["Can explain physical factors affecting population distribution including climate, terrain, soil, and water"]
        U2S3["Can explain human factors affecting population distribution including economy, history, and politics"]
        U2S4["Can define arithmetic density as total population divided by total land area"]
        U2S5["Can define physiological density as total population divided by total arable land"]
        U2S6["Can define agricultural density as number of farmers divided by total arable land"]
        U2S7["Can explain how different density measures reveal different relationships between people and land"]
        U2S8["Can define carrying capacity as the maximum population an area can sustain"]
        U2S9["Can identify major population concentrations including East Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and Europe"]
        U2S10["Can read and interpret population pyramids showing age and sex structure"]
        U2S11["Can identify expansive population pyramids with wide bases indicating high birth rates"]
        U2S12["Can identify constrictive population pyramids with narrow bases indicating low birth rates"]
        U2S13["Can identify stationary population pyramids with roughly equal bars indicating stable growth"]
        U2S14["Can define the dependency ratio as the number of dependents per working-age person"]
        U2S15["Can explain how sex ratios vary across countries due to cultural preferences and migration"]
        U2S16["Can define crude birth rate as the number of live births per 1000 people per year"]
        U2S17["Can define crude death rate as the number of deaths per 1000 people per year"]
        U2S18["Can calculate the rate of natural increase as crude birth rate minus crude death rate"]
        U2S19["Can define total fertility rate as the average number of children a woman will have in her lifetime"]
        U2S20["Can define infant mortality rate as the number of infant deaths per 1000 live births"]
        U2S21["Can define life expectancy as the average number of years a person is expected to live"]
        U2S22["Can calculate doubling time as approximately 70 divided by the natural increase rate"]
        U2S23["Can describe the Demographic Transition Model as showing changes in birth and death rates over time"]
        U2S24["Can identify DTM Stage 1 as having high birth rates and high fluctuating death rates with low growth"]
        U2S25["Can identify DTM Stage 2 as having high birth rates and rapidly declining death rates with high growth"]
        U2S26["Can identify DTM Stage 3 as having declining birth rates and continued low death rates with moderate growth"]
        U2S27["Can identify DTM Stage 4 as having low birth rates and low death rates with very low or zero growth"]
        U2S28["Can identify DTM Stage 5 as having birth rates below death rates resulting in population decline"]
        U2S29["Can explain that improved healthcare and sanitation cause the transition from Stage 1 to Stage 2"]
        U2S30["Can explain that urbanization and changing social norms cause the transition from Stage 2 to Stage 3"]
        U2S31["Can explain how the DTM is linked to levels of industrialization and economic development"]
        U2S32["Can describe the Epidemiologic Transition Model showing changing causes of death through stages"]
        U2S33["Can identify ETM stages from pestilence and famine to degenerative diseases to reemergence of infectious disease"]
        U2S34["Can explain Malthusian theory that population grows exponentially while food supply grows arithmetically"]
        U2S35["Can explain neo-Malthusian concerns about population growth exceeding Earths resource capacity"]
        U2S36["Can explain critiques of Malthus including technological innovation and demographic transition"]
        U2S37["Can describe Ester Boserup theory that population growth stimulates agricultural innovation"]
        U2S38["Can identify pronatalist policies as government efforts encouraging higher birth rates"]
        U2S39["Can identify antinatalist policies as government efforts to reduce birth rates"]
        U2S40["Can identify Chinas former one-child policy as an example of an antinatalist policy"]
        U2S41["Can explain how womens education and access to employment reduce total fertility rates"]
        U2S42["Can explain how access to healthcare and contraception affects population growth"]
        U2S43["Can identify challenges of aging populations including rising healthcare costs and labor shortages"]
        U2S44["Can explain how aging populations increase dependency ratios"]
        U2S45["Can explain government responses to aging such as raising retirement age and increasing immigration"]
        U2S46["Can define migration as a permanent move to a new location"]
        U2S47["Can distinguish between immigration as entering a country and emigration as leaving a country"]
        U2S48["Can define net migration as the difference between immigration and emigration"]
        U2S49["Can distinguish between push factors driving people from a location and pull factors attracting them"]
        U2S50["Can identify economic push-pull factors such as unemployment versus job availability"]
        U2S51["Can identify political push-pull factors such as persecution versus political freedom"]
        U2S52["Can identify environmental push-pull factors such as natural disasters versus favorable climates"]
        U2S53["Can identify demographic push-pull factors such as overpopulation versus available land"]
        U2S54["Can distinguish between voluntary migration by choice and forced migration by compulsion"]
        U2S55["Can define refugees as people who flee their country due to persecution, conflict, or disaster"]
        U2S56["Can define internally displaced persons as people forced to move but remaining within their country"]
        U2S57["Can define asylum seekers as people requesting refugee status in another country"]
        U2S58["Can explain Ravensteins laws of migration including most migrants move short distances"]
        U2S59["Can explain Ravensteins law that long-distance migrants tend to move to major economic centers"]
        U2S60["Can explain step migration as moving in a series of smaller steps toward a destination"]
        U2S61["Can explain the gravity model predicting migration based on population size and distance"]
        U2S62["Can define intervening obstacles as barriers that hinder migration between two points"]
        U2S63["Can define intervening opportunities as closer alternatives that reduce migration to distant places"]
        U2S64["Can define chain migration as migration facilitated by established social networks at the destination"]
        U2S65["Can define guest workers as temporary labor migrants who do not intend to stay permanently"]
        U2S66["Can define transhumance as seasonal movement of livestock between pastures"]
        U2S67["Can define transnational migration as migrants maintaining ties to both origin and destination"]
        U2S68["Can define remittances as money sent by migrants back to their home countries"]
        U2S69["Can explain effects of emigration on origin areas including brain drain and reduced labor"]
        U2S70["Can explain effects of immigration on destination areas including cultural diversity and labor supply"]
        U2S71["Can explain how migration changes the demographic composition of both sending and receiving areas"]
        U2S72["Can define diaspora as the dispersion of a people from their original homeland"]
