    subgraph U3["Unit 3: Cultural Patterns and Processes"]
        U3S1["Can define culture as shared practices, technologies, attitudes, and behaviors of a group"]
        U3S2["Can define cultural traits as individual elements of culture such as food, clothing, or language"]
        U3S3["Can define cultural complexes as groups of interrelated cultural traits"]
        U3S4["Can define cultural hearths as areas where cultural practices originated and diffused from"]
        U3S5["Can identify major early cultural hearths including Mesopotamia, Nile Valley, Indus Valley, Huang He, and Mesoamerica"]
        U3S6["Can distinguish between folk culture as traditional practices of small groups and popular culture as widespread mainstream practices"]
        U3S7["Can explain how folk culture tends to be clustered in specific regions"]
        U3S8["Can explain how popular culture tends to be widely dispersed and rapidly diffused"]
        U3S9["Can define cultural landscape as the visible imprint of human activity on the natural landscape"]
        U3S10["Can identify examples of cultural landscapes including architecture, land use, transportation, and settlement patterns"]
        U3S11["Can explain how religious practices are reflected in cultural landscapes through structures and sacred spaces"]
        U3S12["Can explain the concept of sequent occupance as successive societies leaving cultural imprints on a landscape"]
        U3S13["Can define cultural diffusion as the spread of cultural traits from one place to another"]
        U3S14["Can define relocation diffusion as spread through physical movement of people to new areas"]
        U3S15["Can define expansion diffusion as spread from a source outward while remaining strong at the origin"]
        U3S16["Can define hierarchical diffusion as spread from large or important nodes to smaller ones"]
        U3S17["Can define contagious diffusion as rapid widespread spread through direct contact like a disease"]
        U3S18["Can define stimulus diffusion as spread of an underlying principle even though the trait itself fails to diffuse"]
        U3S19["Can explain how colonialism caused diffusion of European languages, religions, and governance systems"]
        U3S20["Can explain how trade and commerce historically facilitated cultural exchange along routes like the Silk Road"]
        U3S21["Can explain how communication technologies including the internet and social media accelerate cultural diffusion"]
        U3S22["Can explain how transportation technologies increase the rate and reach of cultural diffusion"]
        U3S23["Can define acculturation as the adoption of some traits of a dominant culture by a minority group"]
        U3S24["Can define assimilation as the complete integration of a minority group into the dominant culture"]
        U3S25["Can define syncretism as the blending of two or more cultural or religious traditions"]
        U3S26["Can define multiculturalism as the coexistence and mutual respect of diverse cultures in a society"]
        U3S27["Can classify languages into language families, branches, and groups"]
        U3S28["Can identify Indo-European as the worlds most widely spoken language family"]
        U3S29["Can identify major language families including Sino-Tibetan, Niger-Congo, Afro-Asiatic, and Austronesian"]
        U3S30["Can define lingua franca as a common language used for communication between speakers of different languages"]
        U3S31["Can identify English as a global lingua franca"]
        U3S32["Can define pidgin languages as simplified communication systems between groups without a shared language"]
        U3S33["Can define creole languages as pidgins that become native languages of a community"]
        U3S34["Can define dialects as regional variations of a language"]
        U3S35["Can define isoglosses as boundaries between regions that differ in a specific linguistic feature"]
        U3S36["Can explain how language reflects and shapes cultural identity"]
        U3S37["Can explain how languages become endangered or extinct due to globalization and cultural change"]
        U3S38["Can distinguish between universalizing religions that seek converts and ethnic religions tied to specific groups"]
        U3S39["Can identify Christianity, Islam, and Buddhism as major universalizing religions"]
        U3S40["Can identify Hinduism and Judaism as major ethnic religions"]
        U3S41["Can identify the hearths of major world religions"]
        U3S42["Can explain how universalizing religions spread through missionary activity, conquest, and trade"]
        U3S43["Can explain how ethnic religions remain concentrated near their places of origin"]
        U3S44["Can identify syncretic religions as blending elements of multiple religious traditions"]
        U3S45["Can identify sacred sites and pilgrimage destinations for major world religions"]
        U3S46["Can explain how religion shapes cultural landscapes through architecture, cemeteries, and land use"]
        U3S47["Can define ethnocentrism as judging other cultures by the standards of ones own culture"]
        U3S48["Can define cultural relativism as evaluating a culture based on its own standards and values"]
        U3S49["Can explain how globalization leads to cultural convergence through spread of popular culture"]
        U3S50["Can explain how cultural divergence occurs as groups resist globalization and maintain local traditions"]
        U3S51["Can define placelessness as the loss of unique place identity due to spread of uniform landscapes"]
        U3S52["Can explain how diffusion of popular culture can threaten indigenous and folk cultural practices"]
        U3S53["Can explain how media and technology contribute to both cultural homogenization and cultural awareness"]
        U3S54["Can explain how cultural practices affect gender roles across different societies"]
        U3S55["Can define nativism as the policy of protecting the interests of native-born inhabitants against immigrants"]
