    subgraph U4["Unit 4: Political Patterns and Processes"]
        U4S1["Can define a state as a politically organized territory with a permanent population, defined territory, government, and sovereignty"]
        U4S2["Can define a nation as a group of people who share a common cultural identity"]
        U4S3["Can define a nation-state as a state whose territory corresponds to that of a single nation"]
        U4S4["Can identify examples of nation-states such as Japan and Iceland"]
        U4S5["Can define a multinational state as a state containing two or more national groups"]
        U4S6["Can define a multistate nation as a national group that extends across multiple states"]
        U4S7["Can define a stateless nation as a national group without its own sovereign territory"]
        U4S8["Can identify the Kurds as an example of a stateless nation"]
        U4S9["Can define sovereignty as the supreme authority of a state to govern its territory"]
        U4S10["Can explain self-determination as the right of a people to determine their own political status"]
        U4S11["Can explain how colonialism created many modern political boundaries especially in Africa and Asia"]
        U4S12["Can explain how decolonization created new independent states in the 20th century"]
        U4S13["Can define neocolonialism as economic and political influence by former colonial powers"]
        U4S14["Can define a political boundary as an invisible line separating the territory of states"]
        U4S15["Can define antecedent boundaries as drawn before significant human settlement of the area"]
        U4S16["Can define subsequent boundaries as drawn after human settlement reflecting cultural characteristics"]
        U4S17["Can define superimposed boundaries as forced on a landscape by outside powers ignoring existing cultures"]
        U4S18["Can define relic boundaries as former boundaries that no longer function as official divisions"]
        U4S19["Can distinguish between natural or physical boundaries and geometric or artificial boundaries"]
        U4S20["Can explain the boundary process of definition, delimitation, demarcation, and administration"]
        U4S21["Can identify definitional boundary disputes as disagreements over legal language of a treaty"]
        U4S22["Can identify locational boundary disputes as disagreements over where a boundary should be on the ground"]
        U4S23["Can identify operational boundary disputes as disagreements over how a boundary should function"]
        U4S24["Can identify allocational boundary disputes as disagreements over resource use across boundaries"]
        U4S25["Can explain the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea and Exclusive Economic Zones"]
        U4S26["Can define territorial waters as extending 12 nautical miles from a states coast"]
        U4S27["Can define the EEZ as extending 200 nautical miles from a states coast for resource rights"]
        U4S28["Can explain how gerrymandering manipulates electoral district boundaries for political advantage"]
        U4S29["Can distinguish between packing as concentrating opponents in few districts and cracking as dispersing them"]
        U4S30["Can explain redistricting as the redrawing of electoral district boundaries after a census"]
        U4S31["Can explain reapportionment as the redistribution of legislative seats based on population changes"]
        U4S32["Can define a federal state as dividing power between central government and regional governments"]
        U4S33["Can define a unitary state as concentrating power in the central government"]
        U4S34["Can compare characteristics of federal and unitary systems"]
        U4S35["Can identify characteristics of democratic political systems with free elections and civil liberties"]
        U4S36["Can identify characteristics of authoritarian and totalitarian political systems"]
        U4S37["Can define devolution as the transfer of power from central government to subnational authorities"]
        U4S38["Can explain physical geographic factors that cause devolution such as distance and physical barriers"]
        U4S39["Can explain ethnic separatism as a cause of devolution"]
        U4S40["Can explain economic inequality between regions as a cause of devolution"]
        U4S41["Can identify examples of devolution including Scotland, Catalonia, and Quebec"]
        U4S42["Can define centripetal forces as factors that unify and strengthen a state"]
        U4S43["Can define centrifugal forces as factors that divide and destabilize a state"]
        U4S44["Can identify nationalism, shared culture, and effective infrastructure as centripetal forces"]
        U4S45["Can identify ethnic conflict, economic disparities, and territorial disputes as centrifugal forces"]
        U4S46["Can define irredentism as a states claim to territory in another state based on shared ethnicity"]
        U4S47["Can define terrorism as the use of violence by nonstate actors to achieve political goals"]
        U4S48["Can explain the role of supranational organizations such as the UN, EU, NATO, and AU"]
        U4S49["Can explain how supranational organizations can both support and challenge state sovereignty"]
        U4S50["Can define autonomous and semi-autonomous regions within states"]
        U4S51["Can identify state shapes including compact, prorupted, elongated, fragmented, and perforated"]
        U4S52["Can explain how state shape can affect governance, communication, and internal unity"]
        U4S53["Can define territoriality as the attempt to control a geographic area"]
        U4S54["Can explain Mackinders Heartland Theory identifying interior Eurasia as the key to world power"]
        U4S55["Can explain Spykmans Rimland Theory identifying coastal Eurasia as the key to world power"]
        U4S56["Can define choke points as narrow waterways of strategic importance"]
        U4S57["Can define buffer states as countries between rival powers that reduce conflict"]
        U4S58["Can define shatterbelt regions as areas of political fragmentation and instability between major powers"]
        U4S59["Can identify enclaves as territories entirely surrounded by another state"]
        U4S60["Can identify exclaves as parts of a state separated from the main territory"]
        U4S61["Can define frontier as a zone of no clear political control between states"]
